{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/healthcare-associated-infections/background-information/prevalence/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"194d0e12-5d75-5e09-8fd8-f54ac85d5673","slug":"prevalence","fullItemName":"Prevalence","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 0a0215a9-4b50-4bcd-b729-aa32009aea98 --><h2>How common is it?</h2><!-- end field 0a0215a9-4b50-4bcd-b729-aa32009aea98 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item ddd5afea-4ee9-4345-a16c-aa32009aea51 --><!-- begin field c2d496fe-396d-4346-8efa-aa32009aea98 --><ul><li>Healthcare-associated infections occur across a wide range of clinical conditions and can affect people of all ages.<ul><li>Healthcare workers, family members and carers are also at risk of acquiring infections.</li></ul></li><li>It is estimated that 300,000 people a year in England acquire a healthcare-associated infection as a result of NHS care.</li><li>The most common types of healthcare-associated infection are respiratory infections (including pneumonia and infections of the lower respiratory tract; 22.8%), urinary tract infections (17.2%) and surgical site infections (15.7%). </li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/healthcare-associated-infections/references/\">NICE, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/healthcare-associated-infections/references/\">NICE, 2017</a>] </p><!-- end field c2d496fe-396d-4346-8efa-aa32009aea98 --><!-- end item ddd5afea-4ee9-4345-a16c-aa32009aea51 -->","topic":{"id":"6a4764db-67e6-5a98-ad6f-450c98a82a25","topicId":"97f6f71a-7aa5-40ec-8a1b-aa0600b96730","topicName":"Healthcare-associated infections","slug":"healthcare-associated-infections","lastRevised":"Last revised in May 2019","chapters":[{"id":"6d22e1d5-d924-5b35-8750-a68b353cf1c4","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"7676fe08-e0bb-533d-aaeb-0b6a165afc02","fu